f Subalterns -- t12 A Neutral Place? Anti-Colonialism, Peace, and Revolution in Stockholm, 1917 -- t13 Ethiopia in Swedish Press in the Run-up to the Italo-Ethiopian War, 1935/36 -- tPart IV: Temporal and Spatial Forms of Knowledge Organization -- t14 Cartographic Histories of the Western Territorialization of Northern Australia, 1840s–1900s: Global Circuits of Knowledge and the Mapmakers’ Craft -- t15 National History and Big History: Väinö Auer, the Finnish Nationalist and the Global Environmentalist -- tPart V: The Construction of Temporary and Permanent Representational Spaces and Memory Spaces -- t16 Global Hubs on the Move: Nineteenth- Century World’s Fairs as Spaces of Imagining the World -- t17 Visualizing Sweden at the 1937 World Fair in Paris -- t18 National Museums and the Wider World: The Exclusion of Non-Western Collections at the National Museum of Finland -- t19 A Contested Global Memory Space: The Establishment of the National Museum of Ghana -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume adds to the plurality of global histories by locating the global through its articulation and manifestation within particular localities. It accomplishes this by bringing together interlinked case-studies that analyse various temporal and spatial dimensions of the global in the local and the interactions between the local and the global. The case-studies apply a spatial approach to analyse how global questions of space, movement, networks, borders, and territory are worked out at a local level. The material draws on the Nordic countries, Europe, the Atlantic world, Africa, and Australia and ranges from the seventeenth to the twentieth century. It is further divided into sections that address topics such as the translocality of humans and goods, local articulations of identities and globalities, parliamentarism and anti-colonialism, the organization of knowledge and the construction of spaces of representation and memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aAntikolonialismus. 4aErinnerungsräume. 4aRepräsentationsräume. 4aTranslokalität. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aAnti-colonialism.  aMemory rooms.  aRepresentative rooms.  aTranslocality.1 aEvans, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolke Berge, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHettula, Patrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodacs, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollsten, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansson, Måns, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKananoja, Kalle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaukonen, Emil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoivunen, Leila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlav Hove, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlofsson, Sven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPereira, Edgar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetersson, Fredrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomlid, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRydén, Göran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSablin, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkurnik, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSyrjämaa, Taina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss,